textDisplay: This is the first NYT opinion piece that has grabbed my attention for a decade.   My respect for the paper diminished during the first two years of Obama when the Democrats had all of the power and a charismatic president elected on the promise of hope and change.  Where was the NYT opinion piece at that that time to challenge the Democrats to use its power to address economic inequality, to extend the safety net to millions of households devastated by obvious Wall Street excesses, to expand the Medicare care system to provide a base level of health security for the entire population, to re-examine US foreign policy in the Middle East?   Similarly, where was the NYT opinion piece  in 2016 to challenge the liberal conventional wisdom that Trump supporters were mainly rich and uncaring or racist and stupid?  It raises the question - what does the most influential newspaper in the English speaking world do when it has all of that power?

textDisplay:
It’s also a similar story in the Netherlands. Over the past 20-30 years, its been moving from a social country to one where the most vulnerable get scrutinized based on their last name as to whether they are eligible for child allowances and other services, to the point that last year our prime minister was forced to step down after a controversy surrounding thousands of families with foreign sounding last names who were unjustly stripped of their child credit and asked to pay back thousands of euros with no real form of appeal. This isn’t even mentioning the housing crisis and student loan crisis facing lower income citizens who have essentially no hope of purchasing a property at this point in time.

Meanwhile this same prime minister now looks like he will once again be elected as the leader of the new cabinet (after now continuing to serve almost uninterrupted as “decommissioned prime minister” for the past months). Things don’t change.

textDisplay:
The housing example is a VERY complicated question, I can see why people would want more affordable housing, but I very much sympathize with the existing homeowners. I own my house, and our neighborhood has been, for my entire life, a quiet residential area. My neighbors decided to put up an apartment complex when they moved to a new home. I used to have one, quiet neighbor, now I have dozens. Some are VERY loud, shouting at the top of their lungs at 3am, there's always a gang of thuggish youths hanging around my property, my dogs were pelted with rocks for barking at people despite them being in a well secured and fenced in yard, I've been kept up literally all night by parties that started at 7pm and ended at 11am the next morning. Oh and did I mention the shootings? Yeah, crime in the neighborhood has skyrocketed, burglaries, murders, regular fights, drug dealing, overdoses on the corner, prostitution, you name it, and we've had it here since they put up that apartment complex about 5 years ago, we didn't have those problems 6 years ago.

The reason is simple, none of their tenants stay very long and have no reason to behave as if this is their home, so they act however they desire. This is gonna offend some leftist, but I genuinely don't care, another reason is because the majority of their tenants are illegal immigrants who have no concept of how we live life in our quiet neighborhood and they carry on as if they're in their home country and regularly blast music as loud as they possibly can, well into the night, sometimes they'll turn it off early, but most nights it goes until at least midnight, at which point is usually suddenly cuts off, followed by a LOUD argument. which often sounds like they're going to end up fighting, sometimes they do, sometimes they shoot instead.

There is 15 feet between their complex and my house, how is it possible that I can hear them THAT clearly in my living room over the TV? My living room has to be at least 30 feet away from them, yet it sounds like they're sitting there with me.

Can you even begin to imagine how often I want to go over there with a shotgun? I'm a peaceful man who just wants to live a quiet life, but that apartment complex will turn me into a serial killer, because there has not been a SINGLE day where I wasn't kept up late because of the music or arguing, and if you dare complain about it, they all stand outside your house all night and will surround your car when you leave, thankfully that happened to my neighbor and not me, but the point still stands, we're being bullied into submission by violent, armed thugs who regularly shoot their guns in the neighborhood, sometimes claiming bodies. 6 years ago, I regularly used to walk around my neighborhood, today, I literally fear for my life if I have to walk to the corner store.

That ONE building, has turned my entire quiet neighborhood into a ghetto. I don't care about property value, and I wager that neither do those people, we're concerned about our safety, but we can't say that because it's somehow racist or offensive.

textDisplay:
What’s fueling inequality is our commitment to pigeon holding ourselves to the idea that racism motivates all evils including inequality therefor blinding us to the context and information required to do something about it. It’s become a catch all for every disparity that politically is too hot for scrutiny and devoid of 21st century realities and other factors that are meant to post pone accountability by lazily aligning all evils of inequality to some thought crime, impossible to prove and fruitless to dismantle entirely. The most we can do is what we’ve already done during the civil rights legislation where no race is favored or denied and if so there is recourse. I’m sorry but that’s it legally speaking. The rest is just social conditioning or engineering or promoting special privileges to amend for supposed inequities past. Because access and opportunity is all you can hope to make equal not success. And there are so many factors at play. Yet we use all these examples to express racial prejudice being the driver based on nothing but assumption because for every example there is a counter example that undermines that example and for something to carry so much weight it would have to deliberate and constant. Racism is framed as that with little proof as that tree quotes male e of intent. The current narrative somehow misreads history or the current reality by suggesting that there is a special racial maliciousness enveloping the American people, unseen anywhere else, totally ignorant of the many privileges available to many black and brown peoples not so readily available. And forgetting that racial tensions are a natural effect of diverse societies. Diverse societies themselves that run counter to the notion that such inhabitants as the majority are interested solely in the prospects of their own kind.There are incentives to keep racism at the forefront. an incentive culturally, financially and in principles of moral leverage. As well as a narrative bereft of any challenge to its ubiquity or influence . That to do so somehow amounts to a full denial.
it’s more about cultural
Insecurity, resentment and scapegoat against real self scrutiny and it’s now in the way of solutions to real problems by manner of polluting every concern of this country and thus preventing any real deep dive into any substantive solution. inequality is a cross racial reality and racism a thought crime essentially.

I don’t know enough about america to properly engage with this video, but it smells like a hit piece missing significant nuance. I’d bet a significant portion of money that much of it falls apart under scrutiny.

As a brief example, why are we surprised that middle/ upper class liberals don’t want low income housing in their area? Providing affordable housing doesn’t necessitate the housing being built near them, that’s a logical fallacy. Advocating for more affordable housing can be done without wanting the affordable housing to be inserted into your area of town.

I don’t see why the ‘super rich’ even play in to this video. Clearly an emotional appeal. Worthless argument when you consider that the overwhelming majority of democrat voters aren’t ‘super rich’. Maybe there’s an argument that the ‘Democratic super rich’ don’t live their values, but why would you extrapolate this to the entire group? Very poor journalism, hence why it’s an opinion (worthless) piece.

textDisplay: I'm a Washington State resident and the regressive tax situation here is ridiculous. A couple years ago, I paid attention to all the advisory votes that went to the people regarding taxation. Across the board, people vote against tax hikes of any kind, no matter how useful. I'm lucky enough to be in a position where I could build my current home on a property I bought in town. One of the regulations I had to contend with was land coverage. In my residential zone I'm only allowed to cover 45% of my own property. I find that rather insane. Even with a missing middle push in my area, they have specifically stated that this will not affect permeability limits. So if you don't have enough land to build on, it doesn't matter if the missing middle would allow to build an ADU, you can't create that affordable housing due to lot coverage limits. And big developers, looking to mass generate the most profit at code minimums can work around it. Larger developments can create a central watershed and then use that to reduce the average land footprint of each house and still be within coverage limits. Small builders and single lot remodels like mine can't do that. Throw on top of that the "character of the neighborhood" review I had to go through to get my house approved and you have a bunch of very liberal blue folks making sure they keep the poor out through regulation. Another fun fact, in my town all the apartments in the area feed into one elementary school. All the single family homes feed into another. That's liberal hypocrisy for you.

textDisplay:
Revelation 17:4-5
"The woman was dressed in purple and scarlet and adorned with gold and precious stones and pearls.

She held in her hand a golden cup
full of abominations and the impurities of her sexual immorality.
And on her forehead a mysterious name was written:

BABYLON THE GREAT,
THE MOTHER OF PROSTITUTES
AND OF THE ABOMINATIONS OF THE EARTH
_______________________________________________________
'The New Colossus'

Not like the brazen giant of Greek fame (male)
With conquering limbs astride from land to land; (Colossus of Rhodes, Babylon)
Here at OUR sea-washed, SUNSET GATES shall stand

A mighty woman with a torch,
whose flame Is the imprisoned lightning,
and her name:

Mother of Exiles
_________________________________________________

Jeremiah 51:6-7
"Flee from Babylon! Escape with your lives! Do not be destroyed in her punishment. For this is the time of the Lord’s vengeance; He will pay her what she deserves.

Babylon was a gold cup in the hand of the Lord, making the whole earth drunk. The nations drank her wine; therefore the nations have gone mad."

Revelation 18:2-9
After this I saw another angel descending from heaven with great authority, and the earth was illuminated by his glory. And he cried out in a mighty voice:

“Fallen, fallen is Babylon the great! She has become a lair for demons and a haunt for every unclean spirit, every unclean bird, and every detestable beast. All the nations have drunk the wine of the passion of her immorality. The kings of the earth were immoral with her, and the merchants of the earth have grown wealthy from the extravagance of her luxury.”

Then I heard another voice from heaven say:
“Come out of her, My people, so that you will not share in her sins or contract any of her plagues. For her sins are piled up to heaven, and God has remembered her iniquities.

Give back to her as she has done to others; pay her back double for what she has done; mix her a double portion in her own cup. As much as she has glorified herself and lived in luxury, give her the same measure of torment and grief.

In her heart she says,
‘I sit as queen; I am not a widow and will never see grief.’

Therefore, her plagues will come in one day—death and grief and famine—and she will be consumed by fire, for mighty is the Lord God who judges her.”

Then the kings of the earth who committed sexual immorality and lived in luxury with her will weep and wail at the sight of the smoke rising from the fire that consumes her. In fear of her torment, they will stand at a distance and cry out:
“Woe, woe to the great city, the mighty city of Babylon! For in a single hour your judgment has come.”

And the merchants of the earth will weep and mourn over her, because there is no one left to buy their cargo—cargo of gold, silver, precious stones, and pearls; of fine linen, purple, silk, and scarlet; of all kinds of citron wood and every article of ivory, precious wood, bronze, iron, and marble; of cinnamon, spice, incense, myrrh, and frankincense; of wine, olive oil, fine flour, and wheat; of cattle, sheep, horses, and chariots; of slaves and souls of men.”

Zechariah 14: 12-13
"And this will be the plague with which the Lord strikes all the peoples who have warred against Jerusalem:
Their flesh will rot while they stand on their feet, their eyes will rot in their sockets, and their tongues will rot in their mouths.

On that day a great panic from the Lord will come upon them, so that each will seize the hand of another, and the hand of one will rise against the other."

2 Esdras 15: 28-45
"Behold a horrible vision and the appearance thereof from the East: Where the nations of the dragons of Arabia shall come out with many chariots, and the multitude of them shall be carried as the wind upon earth, that all they which hear them may fear and tremble. Also, the Carmanians raging in wrath shall go forth as the wild boars of the wood, and with great power shall they come, and join battle with them, and shall waste a portion of the land of the Assyrians.

And then shall the dragons have the upper hand, remembering their nature; and if they shall turn themselves, conspiring together in great power to persecute them, Then these shall be troubled bled, and keep silence through their power, and shall flee. And from the land of the Assyrians shall the enemy besiege them, and consume some of them, and in their host shall be fear and dread, and strife among their kings.

Behold clouds from the East and from the North unto the South, and they are very horrible to look upon, full of wrath and storm. They shall smite one upon another, and they shall smite down a great multitude of stars upon the earth, even their own star; and blood shall be from the sword unto the belly, And dung of men unto the camel's hough.

And there shall be great fearfulness and trembling upon earth: and they that see the wrath shall be afraid, and trembling shall come upon them.

And then shall there come great storms from the South, and from the North, and another part from the West. And strong winds shall arise from the East and shall open it, and the cloud which he raised up in wrath, and the star stirred to cause fear toward the East and West wind, shall be destroyed.

The great and mighty clouds shall be puffed up full of wrath, and the star, that they may make all the earth afraid, and them that dwell therein; and they shall pour out over every high and eminent place a horrible star."

Isaiah 30: 25-33
In the day of great slaughter, when the towers fall, streams of water will flow on every high mountain and every lofty hill. The moon will shine like the sun, and the sunlight will be seven times brighter, like the light of seven full days, when the Lord binds up the bruises of his people and heals the wounds he inflicted.

See, the Name of the Lord comes from afar, with burning anger and dense clouds of smoke; his lips are full of wrath, and his tongue is a consuming fire. His breath is like a rushing torrent, rising up to the neck. He shakes the nations in the sieve of destruction; he places in the jaws of the peoples a bit that leads them astray.

And you will sing as on the night you celebrate a holy festival; your hearts will rejoice as when people playing pipes go up to the mountain of the Lord, to the Rock of Israel.

The Lord will cause people to hear his majestic voice and will make them see his arm coming down with raging anger and consuming fire, with cloudburst, thunderstorm and hail.

The voice of the Lord will shatter Assyria; with his rod he will strike them down. Every stroke the Lord lays on them with his punishing club will be to the music of timbrels and harps, as he fights them in battle with the blows of his arm.

Topheth has long been prepared; it has been made ready for the king. Its fire pit has been made deep and wide, with an abundance of fire and wood; the breath of the Lord, like a stream of burning sulfur, sets it ablaze.

textDisplay: This video simplifies the situation in the state of Washington. Progressive income taxes were made unconstitutional in the state by the passage of an amendment to Article 7 Section 1 of the state constitution in 1930, the start of the great depression. In Washington constitutional amendments are passed with super majorities in both chambers of the legislature, and by a majority vote of the people. The feasibility of actually being able to get a super majority in both chambers (requiring republican support) and a vote of the people to consent to an income tax is incredibly low. Progressive lawmakers have been trying to find realistic ways to make this tax structure less regressive by enacting policies like capital gains taxes, with mixed results. Presenting this issue is as simple as liberal hypocrisy is really showing that those speaking on this are missing the context of the political landscape in the state.

textDisplay:
This is the great struggle: to actually live out one’s values. The cynic in me would say that people who profess to do one thing, but in fact do another don’t actually value that which they profess. But that’s only half-true. Paul the Apostle, Buddha, Lao Tzu, and Plato all speak of this struggle.

In Paul’s letter to the Romans: “I don’t really understand myself, for I want to do what is right, but I don’t do it. Instead, I do what I hate… I want to do what is right, but I can’t. I want to do what is good, but I don’t. I don’t want to do what is wrong, but I do it anyway.”

Buddha on the topic: “A man who conquers himself is greater than one who conquers a thousand men in battle.”

Lao Tzu: “He who conquers others is strong; He who conquers himself is mighty.”

And Plato: “For a man to conquer himself is the first and noblest of all victories.”

I live in Portland, OR. And I see the hypocrisy of progressives. But I also see the hypocrisy of conservatives. And I see my own hypocrisy in my own life. It’s all much bigger than politics. Lord have mercy on us all.

It's interesting that you took a detailed look at a housing project in Palo Alto, but when it came to Washingtons taxes as a proportion of income, you didn't bother going into ANY detail. For starters, Washington isn't some mega liberal state. The west side of the State is liberal, the rest of the state isn't, so our actual composition is much closer than it appears. In fact, Republican's controlled the state Senate 4 years ago.

Second, Washington has no state income tax. In fact, income taxes are unconstitutional in the state of Washington. To introduce one would require a constitutional amendment, which begins with a 2/3rd's majority vote in the Senate, which is currently 29 Democrats and 20 Republicans. You'd need all Democrats and 3 Republicans just to get it passed the first step. The last time the people got to vote on a real tax reform bill was in the 1970s.

It's almost like decided the outcome and only reported on the parts that happened to agree with that outcome.

textDisplay:
I like thoughtful discourse and anything that causes people to introspect but I also don't like the rhetoric here. (1) Washington has no state income tax. The inequality is a result of federal taxes, property taxes, and sales taxes. Poorer people pay more because the necessities don't scale with income and someone making 3000x what someone does doesn't have a house worth 3000x or buy things 3000x the rate. They showed Jeff Bezos but his income was $80k so he wouldn't have even been in that bucket. (2) He says "blue states are the problem" in the end. That's a bit sensationalist, no? For instance the educational disparity in the blue states is worse but the education in red states is worse overall. Would you rather move to Louisiana for a more egalitarian education system but its worse? Blue states are moving towards progress and red states by and large aren't. Compare Arkansas to California and you'll find one has more protections for poor renters and the other is the worse place for renters to live overall.

That being said, the educational withholding of funds was the biggest issue here that I wish we could all just get a handle on and decide at the Federal level all children really have the best opportunity a government can afford. As for the NIMBY-ism (although bolstered, at least in California, by a move to protect older people from being priced out of their homes due to rising property taxes), it's a real issue but California isn't going to be affordable as wealthy people can continue to move there. Hoping they can find a way to stabilise prices but there'll never be a drop regardless of who's in charge.

textDisplay:
Interesting. I like the more balanced look-see. Talking about some of the problems and also mentioning where some benefits are.
It's better than most reporting that paints one political side good and the other evil. Which, of course, is most reporting left or right.

That said, I would have preferred graphs and comparative lists with actual numbers. How much worse is Washington than Texas, for instance? Talking about population and rural/urban land allocation would be nice too.


Edit: I found some stats, admittedly from one just one source, so I wouldn't use it for a paper or nothing, but here it is.

Top 1% pays 3% of taxes in Washington and 3.1% in Texas.
Middle 60% pays 10.4% of taxes in Washington and 9.4% in Texas.
Bottom 20% pays 17.8% of taxes in Washington and 13% in Texas.
Still doesn't account for population or rural/urban land allocation, but it's something.

textDisplay: You need a deeper dive into the taxes as ITEP's methodology is REALLY POOR.  The top 6 states have no state income tax, meaning the tax revenues are generated from sales tax, levy-type taxes (cigarettes, gasoline) and property taxes.  Those first two would be considered regressive as everyone pays at the same rate and people with lower incomes are spending a higher % of their income on everyday needs.  Now, these states do tend to have some of the higher sales tax rates.  However, if you're making $30k/yr you are dramatically better off from a tax standpoint, as well as cost of living standpoint, in Texas (which is the 2nd most "regressive" according to ITEP) than in New York, CT or CA.

textDisplay:
3:40 This ‘article’ is asinine. Its cites liberal states and decries them without considering the rest of the country. Sure, building in California has slowed down… but you know where else it has slowed down? EVERYWHERE!!! There is not a state where construction has not slowed down.

4:40 The notion that higher density buildings are somehow supposed to be more progressive is patently absurd. In fact, the more this video continues, the more it seems like a typical conservative diatribe of reasons why we need to squeeze more people into high-density apartments. This isn’t a progressive argument… its pro-corporatist… after all, corporations typically own big apartment complexes.

While, yes, it is possible to lower the cost of units by cramming them all together, this isn’t helpful for addressing the rampant out-of-control real-estate prices caused by corporations buying up properties in order to force an artificial scarcity. The answer here is to force those companies and individuals who are sitting on numerous investment properties to divest of them… not force people to live in smaller and more cramped apartments.

Since 2007, well over 4 million houses have been removed from the real-estate market in order to serve as Airbnb houses. That’s 4 million houses that SHOULD be on the real estate market that are not. Simply limiting the number of Airbnb houses one person may own would have a tremendous impact on available real estate. Another measure which would go a long way would be to prohibit out-of-state purchases which do not include an intent to move into the state within 60 days… and a prohibition on purchases outside the US entirely.

Single-family houses are not the problem… full-stop.

7:40 – This video is correct that Washington State has one of the most regressive tax systems in the US. What this video fails to address is the OVERWHELMING amounts of money that Amazon and Microsoft have put into influencing elections in that state… including vigorously attacking any and all forms of a wealth tax, which would allow the state to shift away from its regressive tax system.

Its strange that this video is quick to identify a cause for real estate issues in California (even if they’re fundamentally wrong), but oddly omits anything resembling a cause for Washington’s regressive taxes.

9:40 – Most of the district disparity in Illinois comes from heavy gerrymandering prior to becoming a Democratic majority. Add to that, there is still a powerfully strong lobbying force that keeps minorities in poorer schools and conservatives in the better funded schools. Again, no consideration of the underlying cause of the problem.

11:20 – So, the game plan here is to just paint each state as entirely one monolithic political group without any sort of nuance whatsoever? No actual delving into any real underlying causes? No consideration of how the opposition parties may or may not have been an undermining impact in each state? I mean, this video is little more than a propaganda -driven narrative development piece. Its utter garbage.

It would be one thing to perform a proper assessment… and there certainly are some issues in liberal states… but nothing offered in this video comes close to being an honest and objective look at what’s going on. Its a poorly developed hit-piece that is concern-trolling blue states.

12:40 – For Democrats to ‘embody their values’ they need more than to control the state. They need support from the federal government, and laws which prevent corporations and the rich from utilizing abusive and manipulative tactics to subvert democracy.... which includes a honest, objective and non-biased news media.

12:50 – And here’s the real message…. “Blue states are the problem”. No they’re not. The complicity of the establishment news media to carry water for conservative propagandists is the problem. Pablum, such as this, is intended to set a false narrative, and convince people that these topics are the real reason for concern… not a news media which fails, time and time again, to ask hard questions and offer up honest criticism, except with a self-serving bias toward clicks and views.

In short? The 5th estate is dead. It has been for a very long time. In its place is a shambling puppet which serves a macabre board of business-as-usual billionaires… and this video has served their purposes. Ironic that the 5th estate is crying hypocrisy while fully engaged in it themselves.

textDisplay:
Great presentation of issues overall l but notice there's a lot of oversimplification over the details.

First for the housing example, there is an obvious concern about land value depreciation for the established residents. A better solution would be zoning new unused land in another part of the city for the high-density apartment complexes instead of inserting it smack dab into the heart of a neighborhood with an established low-density identity. This alleviate the housing concerns and won't upset the original NIMBY residents. Afterall the idea of building a downtown-esque district inside an inhabited surburb seems a little unsound.

Secondly, for taxes there seems to be a misleading idea of how Washington collects their taxes. Washington does not collect ANY INCOME TAX. So whether a person makes 15k/year or 600k/year, they both pay the same amount: $0. The majority of Washington's tax revenue from households stem from spending and property (AKA sales tax and property tax). So the more a person spends, the more they are taxed. Similarly, the more property a person owns, the more they are taxed. Now the demographics diagram shown in the video compares money earned to amount taxed, which again isn't accurate to how Washington's system actually collect taxes. Washington does not collect taxes based on income, but rather consumption. Is this a more regressive system? It's definitely debatable. On one hand it heavily favors savers rather than spenders (which includes the wealthy) on the other hand, workers get to keep more of their paychecks than if it was an income-based model, and they'll have to think about how to spend it wisely. The system's main disadvantage is unable to predict how much of their income the wealthy will actually spend in Washington State (they can also easily purchase goods outside of the state to avoid paying taxes). If they spend the same ratio amount as everyone else in the state (say 20% of their income), then theoretically there won't be any disparity between the demographics.

Thirdly, school funding isn't limited to the county level. The progressivity of school funding varies widely across states in part because of policy decisions local, state, and federal actors make. While education inequality is ultimately decided on the local level, both by the district demographics and the decisions made on their policies, it doesn't exist in a vacuum. To accomodate this, progressive policies made in state and federal level flatten the disparities already present on the local level, each in their own manner. State funding for example tends to correct for inequitable local spending, the states with the most regressive local spending are the ones with the most progressive state spending. Federal funding targets disadvantaged students, i.e. students from low-income households and administer social programs such as the school-lunch program. The states that are the most progressive in school funding also tend to be the most economically segregated. In this case, necessity creates progressive spending.

Issues do need to be addressed when presented, however first we need to understand that it's not all simply black and white.

textDisplay:
This video makes some really weak arguments. If you're going to say that one thing (liberal hypocrisy) "fuels" something as broad and complex as inequality, you need to substantiate that with large-scale and undoubtedly reliable statistics, publications and data. This video achieves the opposite, instead opting to discuss highly limited and specific case scenarios within democratic states, followed by the statement "this is happening all over America". I understand that this is an opinion piece, but it's just too opinionated and crosses the line of being objectively wrong. In no cases was research or analysis by a qualified individual or organisation provided or even cited. Additionally, the video can't seem to decide whether it wants to attack the democratic party or liberal individuals, constantly jumping between blaming problems on "democratic legislature" and blaming problems on individuals that vote or protest against the democratic legislature.

Regardless of your political inclinations, do not listen to this video.

textDisplay:
Those voters want to force other people to do things, but they don’t want things forced upon them. Big surprise—NIMBYs shouting do as I say, not as I do. How about we take force out of the equation. Shrink the government.

For example, if you had less restrictive zoning, you might have developers make cheaper housing that they can charge rent monthly on.

If you had lower taxes, everyone’s tax burden would be a much smaller share of their income.

Instead they want to pull in all this tax money and use it to keep their walled garden the way they want it (bonus points for a Steve Jobs Palo Alto reference) and then complain about people not having the things they’re hoarding.

Congrats though. I like Johnny and I’m surprised the NYT didn’t screw this up. While we may disagree on the ways to fix these issues, these problems are clearly not the fault of Republicans. So thank you for making a fair assessment of the situation. I would point out that many of these issues are the result of regulation, that, absent such control, wouldn’t have such a negative impact on our communities. If you can’t gerrymander school districts, money is distributed equally. The problem is control more so than n people not living their values. In any case, thanks again.

textDisplay: I would like to point out that in the case of Washington's regressive tax system the solution is not as simple as made out in the video.  The reason that Washington's tax system is so regressive is that there are no income taxes and there cannot be any due to the language of the state constitution.  Making an amendment to this constitution would require 2/3 majority of the house and senate, but Democrats do not control 2/3 of the house and senate.  Republicans block those types of amendments.  In fact, we recently tried to enact a new capital gains tax on capital gains of over $250,000 a year.  I believe that is being taken up in the courts to see if it is actually constitutional.

textDisplay: I grew up near the poverty line in a run down 800sq ft shack in rural Oklahoma...as in nothing for 45 minutes around....and 3 hrs drive to a big city with an airport. I just got good grades, went to college on full scholarships, bought a car for $500 when I was 20 and got a job to supplement myself.....my scholarships paid more than my cost of school so I got thousands of dollars back per semester to live on. I left Ok and moved many times, now live near Seattle in a high income bracket. God is good, but I worked very hard, I was a YES SIR YES MA'AM person and worked longer and harder than other around to succeed. So, I don't think where you are born dictates the rest of your life. I know a lot of people who grew up extremely poor (people of all races) and are very successful. You have to want it and not be lazy....some will need to work harder than others...that's true. My parents were married, still are... don't drink, cuss or smoke....raised us going to church 3 times a week and doing charity and being ultra respectful and extremely humble. These are ALL the elements a kid needs....money isn't even that important. Sure we ate a lot of beans and cornbread for dinner but we never went hungry.

textDisplay:
You know what also disincentivizes more housing? Rent control and building red tape. No one wants to build if they don't get a return on building units (zoning is an issue as well though). There's no issue with citizens voting against turning their area into a high density urban area, they should be able to make that choice is is their neighborhood, the issue is when they virtue signal the other way.

For the tax graph that should also be shown as per capita. Based on the numbers shown the 1% are paying 3x their fair share, the top 4% are over paying and then everyone else is under paying with only the lowest earners paying close to their population size. Again it is the top 1%, which is going to be a tiny amount of people and the bald guy wants them to be paying more in taxes overall than 60% of the population combined? To even do that their tax rate would have to be astronomical, it's completely unrealistic.

When it comes to education we've seen time and time again throwing money at the problem does not increase outcomes (granted if the actual building is falling apart an increase will help). You need to institute incentives along with the money, reward well operated schools with great teachers. Throwing cash at a terrible school with no accountability does not improve the situation.

I'm surprised NYT actually made something criticizing the democrats, though the analysis is very simplistic and does not take into account how humans actually react to laws, and incentives and how is the actual best way (outside of rhetoric) to help improve everyone's situation. Some of the policies that democrats actually advocate for are insisted and they actually lead to some of the inequality issues, not the lack of instituting them. That's why, as unsexy or tribalistically fun, you actually need to go through all policies across all the states and see which actually work and pick and chose dem or rep programs and laws that actually work and not get stuck in this binary the two parties push.

Specifically, Washington and Illinois have and do flip control of state government.

When you bring in low income you bring in high rates of substance abuse and all too many people not willing to better themselves and worst impact their communities negatively. So I am all for helping people live better, but in my years I have seen too many not willing to do the hard work not only in terms of employment but in being good neighbors and making that small contribution to maintaining moral standards. So yeah I would hope there can be solutions, but surely see the point in his some communities are trying to protect their standards of living. And keep in mind that when that low income person does rise above by honest hard work and determination, they will certainly want to have a nice neighborhood to move to.

textDisplay: I wholeheartedly agree with the overall point. However, I do think it's slightly misleading to treat the Democratic Party as an ideologically homogenous group. Showing footage of Bernie Sanders, for example, when talking about Democratic hypocrisy on these issues is kind of weird considering Bernie Sanders and his wing of the party are definitely not the reason why these parts of the party platform are not being implemented. The people to blame are corporate Democrats. People like Nancy Pelosi, Hillary Clinton, Barack Obama, Gavin Newsom, Kyrsten Sinema, Andrew Cuomo, etc. The kind who are more concerned with making their corporate and big money donors happy than they are with the well-being of their constituents The kind who are only too happy to use culture wars and identity politics to seem liberal and distract from the fact that, when it comes to actual, substantial change and economic policies, they're actually just conservatives in disguise. The fact that all of these great goals from the party platform aren't being translated into actual policy is not an accident, it's deliberate. That's their system. Say all the right things to get elected and look like the "good guys", then don't actually follow through on your promises (because doing that would upset your wealthy donors) and blame someone else for your failure if anyone notices. Although some of them, like Sinema, just drop the mask entirely. And, unfortunately, these kinds of people run the Democratic party. If people like Bernie Sanders were in charge of the party, things would be different but the corporatists are using every dirty trick in the book to try and keep progressive lawmakers out of power.

textDisplay:
As a Los Angeles resident who does not consider myself liberal for many reasons (but largely the blatant hypocrisy), I don't think the answer to affordable housing is building more apartment complexes, I think the answer is spreading people out (even if that means a mass exodus from many of the cities). People shouldn't be forced to live in tight quarters because they can't afford a home or anything else, we (and I speak as someone who struggles to afford to live here), should be willing to leave and go elsewhere.

And as far as the education thing goes, "school choice" would easily fix many of these issues.

The one thing I will say about conservatives is that they understand their community and care for it much better than liberals do. textOriginal:
As a Los Angeles resident who does not consider myself liberal for many reasons (but largely the blatant hypocrisy), I don't think the answer to affordable housing is building more apartment complexes, I think the answer is spreading people out (even if that means a mass exodus from many of the cities). People shouldn't be forced to live in tight quarters because they can't afford a home or anything else, we (and I speak as someone who struggles to afford to live here), should be willing to leave and go elsewhere.

And as far as the education thing goes, "school choice" would easily fix many of these issues.

The one thing I will say about conservatives is that they understand their community and care for it much better than liberals do. Blue states pretend to care about people, shouting it from the rooftops, while red states actually live by their values and support their communities, and that's why so many have left LA in the past year to go to states like Texas, Arizona, and Montana... And I can't blame them.

textDisplay:
This is why political ideology and "picking a party" irks me so. People use it to hide their real motives on both sides.

I'm a hardcore, dead-nuts pragmatist. The fact that pragmatic, long term thinking and strategies often line up with liberal espousals is purely coincidental for me. I vote mostly liberal because I understand that lifting the bottom lifts us all, and neoliberalism has been tried, persists today, and has spectacularly failed. Pragmatic, long-term cost effectiveness comes from investing in strategies and big-picture issues.

The Alma-ata Primary Health Care for all by 2000 model in the late 70's has shown that despite its initial cost, it has been spectacularly effective in the countries where it was allowed to succeed and wasn't hamstrung right out the gate by the world bank's structural adjustment programs and austerity measures forced upon them by neoliberal ideology. Iran, for example, has astonishingly good public health systems because it also embraced the indirect, expensive contributors like literacy and clean food and drinking water.

The reality of the problem in something like housing is that people who truly think housing is a human right, for the situation to really get better in the long term, they need to "invest" in their community by being willing to take a hit on property value in the short term. My house was worth $400,000 at the beginning of COVID last year. Same time next year, it was worth 500,000. That's great for me. But the average wage earner out here is still stuck at about 60k per household. A $500,000 three bedroom house is absurd for them. 400k was. I would much, much rather my property value shave off $150k, but the community writ large here truly benefit in a long term sustainable way.

textDisplay: This is not accurate. In Chicago, schools are applied to, and parents receive offers via email regardless of your "zone". Yes, it's always easier to go to a school in your neighborhood. This report seems to indicate that the housing in Chicago is valuable 1st and then the schools get the money to be better, but in many cases this happens in the opposite order. The school is good, the kid gets in, and then parents choose to move there. It's the effectiveness of the school that drives the flock of parents to buy in that neighborhood and drive-up the housing prices.

This is the culmination of a lack of viable options for leadership and lazy citizens who dont want to critically think nor put the effort in where it counts. Talk is cheap. Not to mention the lack of empathy for ones neighbor, which I noticed more on the west coast and in big blue cities as opposed to my rural southern towns.

As much as I hate NYT this is an important piece. Though it is a good step, I think some further investigation into both sides of this divide without bias can do much good. When people realize we all want some of the same things, then we have that bridge we can work to build things together with.

textDisplay:
issue with this view of housing in California is they tend to focus on the areas with insane house prices (i.e. silicon valley, downtown LA, San Francisco, etc), however if you move out and away from these areas, house prices in california are not that different than many other states, and you don't even need to go to the rural areas. an example is Moreno Valley or Riverside, house prices aren't insane and also there's a ton of new housing, including new apartments, are going up constantly in Moreno Valley and surrounding.

Intentionally focusing on Palo Alto is really shameful in my opinion, as for the majority of california, Palo Alto is an anomaly caused by the plethora of multibillion dollar corporations inside and surrounding it and the sheer cashflow that pours in and out from it. Silicon Valley is the exception, not the rule for California as there is no other area in California has a housing price crisis as it, not even the Hollywood Hills, Beverly Hills, and Bel Aire, scratches the surface of housing prices of Silicon Valley, not even Sacramento, the state Capital, where housing prices are affordable.
